tools_called.args:
{"query": "What actions are available to protect the reproductive success of commercially fished species?", "summary": "Several actions are available to protect the reproductive success of commercially fished species. Protecting spawning fish from capture can safeguard reproduction directly, with studies showing that spawning and nursery areas closed seasonally or permanently to fishing were used by tagged adult Atlantic cod for nearly a third of time during spawning (Action ID: 2938). Setting a minimum landing size for commercially fished species can protect immature fish before they have the opportunity to reproduce, though one global review found that only one of five swordfish fisheries showed increased recruitment after setting recommended minimum landing sizes, while one study reported that most fish in commercial catches were still immature despite established minimum sizes (Action ID: 2735). 

Temporal restrictions include establishing temporary fishery closures, where tagged adult cod spent nearly a third of time inside a seasonally closed spawning area, providing increased protection during the spawning period (Action ID: 2664). Long-term fishery closures can also protect fish populations, with studies showing higher abundance of young salmon and improved weights of young salmon returning to rivers in the five years after closure of a commercial coastal fishery (Action ID: 2655). Establishing territorial user rights for fisheries demonstrated benefits for reproductive success, with one study finding larger-sized and more numerous egg capsules, and more larvae of Chilean abalone up to 21 months after establishing fishing restrictions compared to open-access areas (Action ID: 2104).

Gear modifications can reduce capture of juvenile fish before they reach reproductive maturity. Using larger mesh sizes in fishing nets improved size-selectivity and reduced catches of unwanted small/undersized fish in 15 of 20 studies across multiple marine regions, allowing juvenile fish to escape and reach reproductive age (Action ID: 2697). Marine Protected Areas that prohibit commercial fishing can protect both spawning grounds and nursery areas, though effectiveness varies by species and implementation (Action ID: 2225).", "action_ids": ["2938","2735","2664","2655","2104","2697","2225"]}

