tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the effects on marine fish populations of prohibiting different types of bottom fishing gear?", "summary": "Studies examining the prohibition of different types of bottom fishing gear show varied effects on marine fish populations. Prohibiting all mobile and static fishing gears that catch bottom species showed mixed results: one study found higher numbers of larger and older cod after 15 years of prohibition, while another found no effect on fish densities after 2-7 years (Action 2654). For fish condition, cod showed better growth in closed areas after 5-15 years compared to openly fished areas (Action 2654).

Prohibiting mobile fishing gears dragged across the seafloor (bottom trawling) had variable effects on fish abundance across studies. Two studies found increased total fish biomass after 15 years and higher biomass of adult red mullet after 14 years, while two other studies found no effect on bottom-dwelling fish abundance after 5 and 10 years of prohibition (Action 2673). For reproductive success, red mullet recruitment increased after 14 years of closure, but haddock recruitment showed no improvement after 7 years (Action 2673). Fish size responses varied: adult red mullet were larger 14 years after closure, but overall fish size effects were mixed across studies and varied by fish group and habitat type (Action 2673).

Prohibiting shellfish dredging specifically showed no effect on bottom-dwelling fish species richness or abundance after 10 years in one North Sea study (Action 2668). Semi-pelagic trawl use instead of bottom trawl reduced commercial fish catch abundance compared to demersal trawling (Action 2118). Areas allowing only hook and line fishing showed greater increases in lobster abundance and size over 4 years compared to fully fished sites (Action 2233).", "action_ids": ["2654","2673","2668","2099","2229","2233","2118","2102"]}

