tools_called.args:
{"query": "What does the evidence say about how different fishing practices affect the survival of fish after capture and release?", "summary": "The evidence shows that different fishing practices significantly affect fish survival after capture and release. Hook and line fishing provides greater fish vitality (an indicator of post-release survival) compared to other gear types (Action 2732). Survival rates vary considerably by species and capture conditions, with studies showing that 76-92% of unwanted small-spotted catshark, thorny skate, pearl perch, and Atlantic wolffish survived for 1 hour to 5 days after capture and release, while less than half of smooth skate survived (Action 2691). Nearly all yelloweye rockfish survived for four days after capture and release, but canary rockfish survival decreased with increasing capture depth (Action 2691). 

Hook type affects survival outcomes - four of seven studies found that using different hook types in longline or recreational fisheries reduced fish hook injuries associated with higher post-release mortality and reduced capture mortality of some unwanted shark and ray species compared to conventional hooks, although other studies found no reduction in post-release mortality for certain species like young sea breams (Action 2698). Circle hooks specifically show mixed survival effects - two studies found similar survival rates for sea turtles caught by circle hooks versus J-hooks, while one review found fewer sea turtle deaths when circle hooks were used in four of five fisheries (Action 3559).

Survival is negatively affected by hooking/capture depth injuries and longer tow durations (Action 2691). Longline configuration modifications also impact survival - nylon hook attachment lines showed higher survival for unwanted sharks and rays compared to wire for two of three species, though one study found reduced survival with nylon hook lines (Action 2699). Different bait types did not increase survival of sharks and rays on gear retrieval according to one global systematic review (Action 2700).", "action_ids": ["2691","2698","2699","2700","2732","3559"]}

