tools_called.args:
{"summary": "Several management actions are available to specifically protect the reproductive capacity of fish populations. Protecting spawning fish from capture is a direct management approach that involves seasonal fishery closures to protect spawning individuals, with studies showing that spawning areas closed seasonally or permanently to fishing were used by tagged adult Atlantic cod for nearly a third of time during spawning (Action ID: 2938). Releasing males of species known to guard nests during breeding season is another targeted approach, though no studies have yet evaluated its effects on marine fish populations (Action ID: 2734).

Establishing temporary fishery closures provides broader protection, with studies showing that tagged adult cod spent nearly a third of time inside seasonally closed spawning areas during implementation, providing increased protection from fishing gears during the spawning period (Action ID: 2664). Setting minimum landing sizes for commercially fished species helps protect immature fish before they reach reproductive maturity, though one study reported that despite established minimum sizes, most fish landed in commercial catches were immature and had never spawned (Action ID: 2735).

Additional management approaches include allowing periodic fishing only, with one study finding that protected areas fished only for short periods had greater biomass than openly fished areas and similar fish biomass as areas permanently closed to fishing (Action ID: 2679). Size range specifications and maximum landing size limits are also available management tools, though no studies have yet evaluated their specific effects on fish reproductive capacity (Action IDs: 2737, 2736).", "action_ids": ["2938","2734","2664","2735","2679","2737","2736"], "query": "What management actions are available to specifically protect the reproductive capacity of fish populations?"}

