{"query": "What is the state of evidence for the effectiveness of involving fishers and other stakeholders in marine conservation management?", "summary": "The evidence for the effectiveness of involving fishers and other stakeholders in marine conservation management is extremely limited. Action 2910 reports that only three studies examined the effect of involving fishers and stakeholders in co-management on marine fish populations, conducted in the Indian Ocean, South China Sea (Vietnam), and Pacific Ocean (Tonga). The results showed mixed effectiveness: one study found increased overall fish abundance nine years after implementation, while another found no increase in total fish catch rates and decreased catch rates in half of the six species groups after five years. One study reported decreased illegal fishing using destructive fishing gears after co-management was established, but another found no decrease in overall fishing effort after five years of implementation.

For most other stakeholder involvement approaches, no studies were found that evaluated their effects. Actions 2813, 2809, 2243, 2814, and 2812 all report that no studies were found evaluating the effects of engaging stakeholders/fishers in scientific research and data collection, including fishers in management groups for marine protected areas, engaging with stakeholders when designing Marine Protected Areas, promoting knowledge exchange between fishers, or involving stakeholders in allocation of harvest rights.

Limited evidence exists for related approaches: Action 2242 found that community-based fisheries management resulted in higher New Zealand scallop abundance but smaller scallop size compared to other management types. Action 2104 found that territorial user rights for fisheries led to larger-sized and more numerous egg capsules and more larvae of Chilean abalone compared to open-access areas.", "action_ids": ["2910","2813","2809","2243","2814","2812","2242","2104"]}

