{"query": "What are the documented effects of different restrictions on line fishing, such as prohibitions or gear modifications, on fish populations and unwanted catch?", "summary": "Based on the documented evidence, different restrictions on line fishing show varying effects on fish populations and unwanted catch. Prohibiting line fishing altogether has shown positive effects on fish populations - one study found that prohibiting offshore line fishing and all other boat-based fishing in a marine protected area resulted in higher abundances of four of four fish species over-exploited by line fishing, and these species were also larger in size compared to areas where fishing was permitted (Action 2671). Prohibiting certain gear types generally reduces unwanted catch - a study in the Kattegat found that prohibiting non-selective gear types combined with fishery closures reduced unwanted catch of cod, and another study in the Indian Ocean found higher fish density in areas where all but one gear type was prohibited compared to areas with fewer restrictions (Action 3810).

Regarding gear modifications, longline configuration changes show mixed results for unwanted catch reduction. Modifying longline configuration such as increasing lead weights or using nylon instead of wire hook attachments reduced unwanted shark and ray catches in some cases but not others, with one review finding reductions in one of two cases examined. Survival rates of unwanted sharks and rays varied depending on the modification - nylon hook attachments showed higher survival for two of three species but lower survival for one species compared to wire attachments (Action 2699). Different bait types had inconsistent effects - six of eight studies found that using different bait types reduced unwanted catches of various species including undersized haddock and Atlantic cod, while two studies found no reduction in unwanted catches, and global reviews found no effect on unwanted shark and ray catches (Action 2700).

Gillnet modifications showed promising results for reducing unwanted catch - three of four studies found that modifications including reduced height, increased mesh size, and changes in twine diameter reduced unwanted catch of cod, discarded commercial and non-commercial species, though one study found no reduction in unwanted shark catches (Action 2701). Additional gear modifications like escape grids and panels in trawl nets also showed effectiveness, with three of four studies finding reduced unwanted fish and shark catches when these devices were fitted to nets (Action 2726).", "action_ids": ["2671","3810","2699","2700","2701","2726"]}

